The ggplot object

  • ggplot2 is a library to build data graphics
  • The reason that ggplot2 has been so successful is that it allows you to build graphics incrementally
  • The first thing we do is create a ggplot object
  • There are two methods for doing this (I prefer the second, as it makes it clearer at a glance what all the aesthetics and layers are)
# Book Method - Assign a variable the ggplot object
# Then use that variable to build upon
g <- ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp))
g + geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# I prefer to keep the object unassigned so I can see all the parts
# This becomes especially useful as you build your graphics over huge scripts
ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

What are we Looking at Here?

  1. The ggplot object
    • This informs which data to use - in this case CIACountries and then which aethestics to use with the aes() function
    • Here, we are telling ggplot to use the educ column for the x position and gdp for the y position
  2. The geom_point() layer
    • This is the glyph we want to plot
    • Each point is a different country, located at its educ and gdp
    • Note: the size for each point is the same, so it is not an aesthetic (it does not map to a visual cue)

Adding More Visual Cues

  • You can add additional aesthetics beyond x and y.
  • You can add them in the ggplot object (if they will be used universally) OR
  • You can add them in the layer object
ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users))
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

To Change an Aestetic or Not, That is the Question

You can also customize a layer universally (not based on a variable in the data)

In the code below, we change the size of the dot to be bigger for all dots (still not a visual cue, but does make the plot easier to read).

ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users), size = 3)
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

We can, however, also make size an aesthetic (and add even more information to the plot)!

Note: There is a such a thing as too much information in a plot be careful not to add too many aesthetics.

ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(aes(color = net_users, size = roadways))
## Warning: Removed 66 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Lets get Wild - there is a World of Things to Change

  • All of these features can be assigned via aes() or not (which makes them universal changes)
  • alpha is the one that may seem less intuitive, it is the opacity (between 0 and 1)
  • color (or colour, if you prefer) is the color of lines
  • fill is the color filling an object (like a bar or the squares below)
  • There are a bunch of shapes built in (I googled it and there is a list)
ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_point(size = 3, 
               color = "purple", 
               alpha = 0.5, 
               shape = 22, 
               fill = "pink")
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Going Beyond Points

  • Obviously there are more than just scatter plots in this world
  • You can build any plot you can imagine with ggplot2 (I may not have a great imagination)
  • Check out the ggplot2 cheat sheet on the RStudio Website or our Google Drive
ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp)) +
    geom_text(aes(label = country, color = net_users))
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_text).

The Beat and the Chorus at the SAME TIME!

Were not really ready for this yet, but we can add multiple layers, too!

ggplot(data = CIACountries, aes(x = educ, y = gdp, color = net_users)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_text(aes(label = country), 
              nudge_x = 0.15, 
              check_overlap = TRUE, 
              hjust = 0)
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
## Warning: Removed 64 rows containing missing values (geom_text).
